replies.bodyText:
If an object can be modified while another thread reads/writes it, the operation shall be thread-safe, although if it's very unlikely the two threads accessing the same resource concurrently. You could write the following to make it thread-safe:
private ArrayList<UpnpEntry> currentQueue = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>());

The volatile can be omitted, since the reference currentQueue is only set during class initialization.
If you loop over the list, the whole operation shall be synchronized:
synchronized (currentQueue) {
   currentQueue.forEach(...);
}

@fwolter Thank you for this explanation.
When I look at the specific example, currentQueue is actually not only set during class initialization. In the class initialization, it is just initialized with an empty ArrayList default. It actually is set in the registerQueue method (L696 of UpnpRendererHandler), where a new queue is passed in and completely replaces the previous one. No writes are done inside the currentQueue anywhere in the code, except full replacement of the full queue. All the rest is only reads. Do I still need synchronization for this? That's also why I think volatile is required.
I am going through the code again and looking for other potential synchronization issues.

